title: For Sale:  Japanese T-99 Arisaka Last Ditch
postcontent:
This Type 99 Arisaka is a series 11 "Last Ditch" rifle made at the Nagoya Army Arsenal located in Torimatsu. The common thinking is that all of this series rifles were produced in 1945. This example has a matching bolt and receiver.The pictures included with this listing show a fair and accurate representation of this weapons condition. Please feel free to ask any questions you may have about this or any of my firearms. 

As the war progressed, more and more cost saving measures were  employed to reduce the demand for raw materials and increase production speed. First introduced in 1939, the Type 99 Arisaka included several interesting, albeit functionally unnecessary features such as a folding mono-pod and anti-aircraft sights. However, the Type 99 also employed features which were very beneficial as well as useful to the infantry soldier and included a chrome lined barrel, a first for a production military weapon, as well as adjustable sights. As the tides of war began turning against the Japanese in 1943 and  resources were becoming increasingly scarce, production and the design of the Type 99 began to change dramatically. The mono-pod and anti-aircraft sights were the first features to be eliminated. The full length cleaning rod was replaced by a much shorter version designed to be pulled through the bore. Later production design changes saw the shortening of the hand-guard to reduce the need for wood, as well as the metal butt-plate being replaced by a simple thin wooden plate which was held in place with nails. Next to go were the  dustcover, adjustable sights and the protective ears surrounding the front sight. The checkering on the safety knob was also eliminated and by the end of WWII the Type 99 Arisaka bore little resemblance its original design.

	So many changes resulted in the rifle being referred to as the "Substitute Standard Type 99", now simply referred to by collectors as a "Last Ditch" rifle.

 The Arisaka rifle was never imported into the U.S. in great numbers and as a result most of the rifles which are now in collections, were brought home from the Pacific Theater by Marines and Army Soldiers who fought during the Pacific Campaign.

title: For Sale:  Japanese Type 92 Machine Gun ammo and clip circa 1939 w original box label dated 1939
postcontent:
The Type 92 heavy machine gun entered service for the Japanese Imperial Army in 1932 and was the standard heavy machine gun unemployed by Japanese forces during WWII. The Type 92 HMG is an air cooled, strip fed, gas-actuated machine gun based on the Hotchkiss M1914. Chambered for 7.7x58mm, the Type 92 HMG was capable of utilizing both the rimless and semi-rimed cartridge used by the Japanese main battle rifle, the Type 99 Arisaka.

Nicknamed the "woodpecker" by Allied soldiers because of the distinctive sound this weapon produced when fired. This weapon was intended to be maned by a 3-man machine gun crew. With a cyclic rate of 450 RMP and muzzle velocity of approximately 2,400 fps This weapon represented a formidable obstacle for the Allied forces who faced it.  

This offering is for one original 1939 dated Japanese Type 92 machine gun clip loaded with 30 rounds of 7.7x58 mm armor piercing ammo. This offering comes complete with the original WWII packaging and printed label with sharp clear markings dated "14.9". all of which are in excellent condition. The Japanese date code of "14.9" corresponds to September 1939. This is a wonderful opportunity to own a great piece of history and enhance your collection.

title: For Sale:  Japanese Type-30 Nagoya Bayonet
postcontent:
The Nagoya Arsenal was one of Japan's primary manufactures of firearms and bayonets. Bayonet  production by Nagoya itself are early models dating to 1936-37. After this time period, greater demands were made for weapons of all types. To answer this call for increasing the weapons needed for WWII The Nagoya Arsenal began acting as a supervising/quality control entity for a number of other subcontractors who were also producing bayonets. This particular bayonet bears only the Nagoya Arsenal mark, identifying its DOM in the 1936-37 range. During this time period Japan was preparing to invade China and began laying the ground work for WWII. While I have no confirming provenance proving this bayonet was actually used in WWII, given its DOM and the events surrounding this time period, I believe there is a very good chance this weapon did indeed see action in WWII.

Overall this bayonet and scabbard are in good to very good condition. The blueing on the bayonet itself has been replaced by the patina of time, the blade itself has NOT been sharpened and the wooden handles remain tight. The pictures included with this listing show a fair and accurate representation of this weapons condition. Please feel free to ask any questions you may have about this or any of my listings.

title: For Sale:  1906 FN (Baby Browning) 25 auto-1st variant-Belguim
postcontent:
The FN Browning of 1906
Browning’s vest pocket pistol was essentially a miniaturized version of the Model 1903 with a striker to ignite the cartridge (in place of the hammer used in the earlier design) and with no manual safety. Browning offered the diminutive pistol to Colt’s as early as 1904, but they turned him down, so he took the design to FN, who manufactured it as the Pistolet Browning 6.35mm. FN received Browning’s prototype in 1905, and the first production pistols went on sale in July 1906. 
The first variant of the FN Browning Model 1906, like Browning’s prototype, had no manual safety and featured only a grip safety. There was no mechanism to hold the slide open, either for reloading or for disassembly.  The early trigger was a narrow, flat piece of machined metal, curved in front to fit the finger, with a smooth surface. Approximately 130,000 of the first variant guns were manufactured between 1906 and 1909. . This was made by Fabrique Nationale in Herstal, Belgium. The barrel is 2" long.
These guns sell for over $500 if you can find one. This one has very nice bluing and would make a great collector pistol or use.  Fires fine. Includes hardcase and ammo (2/3 box). Hard to find in this condition and price!

Cash, face-to face. Proof of age (DL) and bill of sale. Would consider FFL to FFL transfer.  Sorry not interested in trades at this time.

title: For Sale:  Armslist is not a Discussion Forum! Please Stop Cluttering the Ads!
postcontent:
I'm completely condtradicting myself by writing this post but I'm going to do it anyway 

Armslist Classifieds are just that - intended to be classifieds; not a discussion forum (I believe Armslist actually has a forum though) for letting the world know what you think of everything. Personally, I really don't care, nor do most people care what you think of people's asking prices or different Gun Shows that you don't like!

It seems that these classifieds are getting more and more polluted with annoying crap posts like this. Everyone is entitled to their opinion, but there are appropriate places to voice them - the classifieds section of AL is not one of them!

If something is priced to high in your opinion; simply don't buy it and move on with your life...nobody has authority to regulate what someone can ask for something and if something is higher than you feel it should be priced; it's the potential buyer's decision and responsibility to educate themselves - It's not your responsibility.  

Please take these kinds of annoying posts to an appropriate place and leave the Armslist Classifieds for classifieds ads.

title: For Sale:  British Enfield No.2 Mark1 38-200 Revolver
postcontent:
Own a piece of history!  Chambered for .38-200, (not a 38 special) a cartridge specifically designed for military use, the Enfield No. 2 Mk 1 was the standard British sidearm in the Second World War. The No. 2 Mk 1 was born when British authorities began searching for a double-action revolver with less weight and recoil than the Webley they'd been using, that could be quickly mastered by a minimally-trained soldier and gave him a good probability of hitting an enemy with the first shot at extremely close ranges. The .38-200 round was created by combining a .38 S&W catridge with a 200 grain bullet. By using such a long, heavy, round-nosed lead bullet in a .38 caliber cartridge, it was found that the bullet, being minimally stabilized for its weight and caliber, tended to tumble longitudinally when striking an object, theoretically increasing wounding and stopping ability of human targets at short ranges. This double-action-only revolver features a fixed blade front sight with a rear groove, grips, and a saddle ring. Its metal is in fair condition and its bore is in good condition.
Cabelas & GM both listed their gun for over $500 (have copies of ads).
Includes vintage LH leather basketweave holster and box of shells.
Asking $295.00

If you ever watched Lawrence of Arabia-he had a sidearm like this.

Cash Face-to-face.  Must have proof of ID/age (DL) and sign bill of sale.  
Would consider FFL to FFL transfer.
Sorry, not interested in trades at this time.

title: For Sale:  Ruger Mark I pistol
postcontent:
Standard (1949-1981) In many ways the Standard model is a groundbreaking design, lacking the slide found on conventional pistols, instead it sports a cylindrical bolt which cycles inside a tubular receiver in a manner more characteristic of a rimfire rifle. The bolt of the pistol features protruding “ears” at its rear which are grasped and pulled rearward to feed the initial round and cock the action. Using the basic blowback form of operation, the Standard model originally came with a blued carbon steel finish and was equipped with a 4.75-inch (12.1 cm) tapered barrel.

the 7 digit ser# starts with 44 so I believe it is a 1967.  This gun is in awesome condition with few handling marks.  I am not an expert but if I was collecting guns this one would be hard to beat. Bluing is great and appears to have had little use.

Comes with new soft-sided holster, 2 clips and manual (original but not original to this specific gun). This is not your "average/worn" Mark I. This pistol is way above average. Plus the extra mag and holster cost around $60. (have you tried to find a mag in a store for a Mark I or Mark II?).  The holster is made for this pistol (new).  You may find one cheaper but it would be hard to find one nicer. My price is firm.
